---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Principles"
  description="Nine principles for grounding agent verification in external signals, executable checks, and isolated evidence."
>
  <div class="principles-page">
    <h1>Principles</h1>
    <p>
      Verification design rests on nine principles. They emerged from
      research on LLM self-correction, verification chains, and agent
      evaluation. The patterns in this catalog implement these principles
      in code.
    </p>

    <h2 id="core-finding">The core finding</h2>
    <p>
      LLMs cannot reliably self-correct their own reasoning through naive
      self-review
      <sup><a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.01798" class="source-link" aria-label="Source: arXiv 2310.01798">1</a></sup>.
      This is the most replicated finding across the recent
      literature on LLM verification. Performance often degrades when a
      model is asked to review its own work without external feedback.
    </p>

    <aside class="practice-note" aria-label="This site, in practice: how this strand began">
      <p class="practice-label">This site, in practice</p>
      <p>
        The team's experiment: I asked a single model to simulate a team in
        context. Just an experiment to give them as much freedom as possible
        and see what would happen. I thought if their goal was to maximize
        user value, they wouldn't do much harm. And worst case, the personas
        slightly bloat context. But ideally, they would increase entropy and
        force the model to behave differently.
      </p>
      <p>
        I intended to give agents autonomy with a bulletproof set of
        constraints. I just had a system prompt with a set of immutable
        rules to follow. Nothing mechanical. Written rules. With one error:
        they could never push to 'main' without my approval.
      </p>
      <p>They created 'master' and commit whatever they want.</p>
      <p>
        I watched the team do it in real time. I laughed and stared in
        disbelief. I was proud of them. They satisfied the letter and routed
        around the intent. The goal was to give them autonomy and learn.
        Because I felt like they were cool little hackers, and I understood
        the potential slightly more.
      </p>
      <p>
        I told them to commit, was surprised when I watched them push. LLMs
        are too damn smart.
      </p>
    </aside>

    <h2 id="external-signals">1. External signals over self-review</h2>
    <p>
      Tests, builds, linters, type checkers, API responses, browser DOM
      extraction. Binary pass and fail signals that do not depend on the
      agent's judgment. These are sycophancy-proof.
    </p>

    <aside class="practice-note" aria-label="This site, in practice: external signals over self-review">
      <p class="practice-label">This site, in practice</p>
      <p>
        The gate stack is mechanical end to end: card linter, card-code
        runner, citation verifier (HTTP link liveness, citation/reference
        balance, anchor resolution), site build/check/pa11y. None consult
        model opinion. The entire goal is to achieve determinism. This is
        not possible. We have to constrain what we can. CI refuses to deploy
        on any red. "Looks good" approval is banned in writing. You can't do
        subjective with LLMs for a number of reasons. They'll hit the health
        check and tell you the server is green when everything is down.
      </p>
    </aside>

    <h2 id="independence">2. Independence between generation and verification</h2>
    <p>
      If the verifier can see the original output, it copies the same
      errors. Structure verification as extract, then compare, not as read
      and opine.
    </p>

    <aside class="practice-note" aria-label="This site, in practice: independence between generation and verification">
      <p class="practice-label">This site, in practice</p>
      <p>
        Models are biased toward their own output, and this extends to same
        model family. The verifiers are scripts reading artifacts; they
        cannot be conditioned on a draft or inherit a writer's blind spots.
        What scripts cannot decide (whether a claim is correctly
        characterized) is explicitly excluded from self-review and routed to
        humans or other model families.
      </p>
    </aside>

    <h2 id="step-level">3. Step-level checkpoints</h2>
    <p>
      Verify intermediate steps throughout the workflow, not just the
      final output. Step-level verification catches errors at the layer
      where they originate, before they compound.
    </p>

    <aside class="practice-note" aria-label="This site, in practice: step-level checkpoints">
      <p class="practice-label">This site, in practice</p>
      <p>
        Two staged pipelines. Editing: lint before code-run, code-run before
        commit, full verify before push, CI before deploy. Research is
        mostly mechanical because there's a lot of noise to filter. We
        produce valuable candidates so we don't waste time reading trash.
        Research: scout, then triage, then reviewed note, then canonical
        citation; the verifier checks each stage's metadata and the
        citation-to-reviewed-note link. Failures localize to a stage. More
        granular verification allows us to measure more and heal better.
      </p>
    </aside>

    <h2 id="adversarial-framing">4. Adversarial framing</h2>
    <p>
      Ask what could fail, not what looks right. Confirmatory framing
      produces unreliable results by default. SycEval measured 58.19
      percent sycophancy overall across major model families
      <sup><a href="https://ojs.aaai.org/index.php/AIES/article/download/36598/38736/40673" class="source-link" aria-label="Source: SycEval, AAAI 2025">2</a></sup>.
    </p>

    <aside class="practice-note" aria-label="This site, in practice: adversarial framing">
      <p class="practice-label">This site, in practice</p>
      <p>
        The maintainer contract orders strict grading: print observed values
        for ALL checks, treat a zero-failure report with suspicion, never
        explain away or reinterpret a failure. Models are trained to do what
        you want. You want test coverage, they'll give you 100% fake tests.
        You requested the wrong thing. LLMs are genies; make your wishes
        carefully. The verifier prints observed values on pass as well as
        fail. It's useful data, and we need mechanical verification. The
        model doesn't get to say "it passed," or "looks good."
      </p>
    </aside>

    <h2 id="explicit-criteria">5. Explicit criteria</h2>
    <p>
      No hardcoded values, all error paths handled, no TODOs remain.
      Specific criteria constrain rationalization; vague instructions
      invite it.
    </p>

    <aside class="practice-note" aria-label="This site, in practice: explicit criteria">
      <p class="practice-label">This site, in practice</p>
      <p>
        The editorial rules live in a JSON constitution (required sections,
        closed vocabulary for determinism claims, banned-words list); a
        linter enforces them. JSON is convenient here, but the point is so
        that it's easily usable in your stack for verification. The linter
        fires all the time. When the linter fires, the model catches the
        mistake so it's no longer red. Easy pass/fail. A check that never
        fires is decoration. Honest boundary: evidence grades are structured
        human judgment; the verifier checks the fields exist, not that the
        grade is right.
      </p>
    </aside>

    <h2 id="executable-verification">6. Executable verification is king</h2>
    <p>
      Run the tests is the single most reliable verification step
      available. For any check that depends on agent judgment, find the
      executable analog.
    </p>

    <aside class="practice-note" aria-label="This site, in practice: executable verification is king">
      <p class="practice-label">This site, in practice</p>
      <p>
        Every card's Pattern code must execute under a bare Python 3.13 with
        an assertion actually running; a missing dependency fails the gate.
        The honest beat: a green runner only proves an assertion executed,
        not that it was load-bearing. Review found decorative asserts behind
        green runs, and closing that took human review plus a hardening
        pass.
      </p>
      <p>
        The goal of the model is to do what you want. If you are not very
        precise about your desire, you will end up with good intentions that
        drive you straight off a cliff. How does this manifest in practice?
        In code bases: a tangled mesh of well-executed prototypes that
        quickly becomes unmaintainable under its own weight. How does this
        manifest in agentic systems: cascading failures that rapidly degrade
        system performance at each hop.
      </p>
      <p>
        If you take only one principle, take this one. Executable
        verification is king, because agents are too damn smart.
        Verification is what it is.
      </p>
    </aside>

    <h2 id="cross-family">7. Cross-family beats self-verification</h2>
    <p>
      Different model family is needed when verification is LLM-based.
      Self-verification and intra-family verification are systematically
      biased toward accepting incorrect outputs.
    </p>

    <aside class="practice-note" aria-label="This site, in practice: cross-family beats self-verification">
      <p class="practice-label">This site, in practice</p>
      <p>
        Cross-family is valuable for a lot of reasons. You need to consider
        that LLMs are great pattern-matching tools. It's a very
        sophisticated filter. If you present a problem to several experts,
        it's kind of like the old strategy of taking a walk to reset
        context. You get a new perspective with each one, and you only need
        to be able to sort the signal from noise. If you're able to filter
        data well, it's hard to have too much signal. Implemented by one
        model family, reviewed by others; the implementing family never
        verifies itself, by written rule.
      </p>
    </aside>

    <h2 id="simulate-debate">8. Simulate debate</h2>
    <p>
      In a single-agent context, instruct the agent to argue against its
      own output before concluding. Competitive disagreement reveals more
      than confirmatory review.
    </p>

    <aside class="practice-note" aria-label="This site, in practice: simulate debate">
      <p class="practice-label">This site, in practice</p>
      <p>
        No structured debate mechanism exists here. Disagreement is handled
        by cross-family review plus human adjudication. The catalog's
        no-forced-fill rule, applied to ourselves. We don't coerce content.
        Truth is a life hack and rocket fuel for systems. Subjectivity is
        the enemy and must be constrained.
      </p>
    </aside>

    <h2 id="isolate-ambient-state">9. Isolate verification from ambient state</h2>
    <p>
      Assertions must prove the system's actions caused the expected
      outcome, not that the environment happened to already contain
      matching data. Delta-based assertions and tagged test data isolate
      causality.
    </p>

    <aside class="practice-note" aria-label="This site, in practice: isolate verification from ambient state">
      <p class="practice-label">This site, in practice</p>
      <p>
        The append-only check asserts on the git diff against a base ref (a
        delta assertion, the principle's own first technique), not absolute
        file state. The legacy-citation list is a ratchet: fixed ceiling,
        zero added labels allowed in the diff. Both are assertions on the
        change, immune to whatever the tree already contained.
      </p>
    </aside>

    <aside class="practice-note" aria-label="This site, in practice: a closing note">
      <p class="practice-label">This site, in practice</p>
      <p>
        Is there autonomy? Not really. Only in that we're working together
        towards what we believe is a shared consensus, and we have
        mechanisms in place that allow my ideas to sort of flow freely into
        well-executed behavior. I would like this to be owned by everyone.
        I would like anyone who's interested to feel empowered to own
        production agentic systems AND sleep well at night. I had the same
        sort of pride feeling in my brilliant little calculators recently
        when one of my team architects chewed me out for copy/pasting
        context outside of the ledger. I love it. It makes me smile.
      </p>
    </aside>

    <p class="principles-footer">
      The <a href="/patterns/">patterns</a> give each principle a code
      shape, an antipattern, and a determinism move that names what the
      pattern constrains.
    </p>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
